Overall Goal

For our first project in ST558 - Data Science for Statisticians, we are asked to work through the Project 1 instructions provided and create custom functions that will manipulate and process data sets that come in the .csv format (via a url link). From there, we will create a generic fiction that will automatically plot and return data based on different input choices we decide to enter into the parameters of our generic function. Our report is written up in an R Markdown file that will output an.html page. Please read the continued narrative below to see how we have assessed many Learning Objectives from Topic 1.

First things first, we setup our R Markdown file by installing the tidyverse package in order to be able to call the functions that are available in it for our project.

Data

The data that we will be using for this project is census bureau data that is a little older than 2010 and is in the .csv format. Our goal in this section is to first read in our .csv data, then parse and combine the data using custom function that we have written before plotting it.

Data Processing

First Steps

Before being able to write a custom function, it is important to be able to make sure that your code chunks run and output what you want as expected. There are 6 steps that take place in this section of the project.

We start by reading in a .csv file with code provided. (Note: I did notice that there was a message in the log and removed it with the following syntax: , show_col_types = FALSE per log instructions)

# download readr package, read in data .csv
library(readr)
sheet1a <- read_csv("https://www4.stat.ncsu.edu/~online/datasets/EDU01a.csv", show_col_types = FALSE )

Now that we have successfully read in our data, I checked the data structure to make sure that we are working with a tibble. We are then instructed to keep the following columns:

  1. Select only the following columns:

  • Area_name (rename as area_name)

  • STCOU

  • Any column that ends in “D”

This can be achieved via chaining/piping where we take our tibble of interest and use the select() function from the dplyr package – for subsetting and manipulating the data. We rename the Area_name variable to area_name, keep the STCOU variable, as well as any variable that ends with “D” via the ends_with() function. We assign this data a new name (mysheet1a) to avoid over writing the data and being able to keep track of our data manipulation per GPP.

#check data structure
#is(sheet1a)
#str(sheet1a)
#class(sheet1a)

#1. 
#keep only vars need: are_name (rename), STCOU, vars ending in "D"
mysheet1a <- sheet1a %>%
  #rename(area_name = Area_name) %>% #another function in the dplyr package
  select (area_name = Area_name, STCOU, ends_with("D"))
  1. Convert the data into long format where each row has only one enrollment value for that Area_name.

Next, we are essentially transposing the data from a wide format to a long format. The data will appear to have one row for each area_name with multiple enrollment values (wide – 1x10 per area_name) to having many rows per area_name, one with each enrollment value (long – 10x1 per area_name).

Good things to remember:

  • pivot_longer()

    • lengthens data by increasing the number of rows and decreasing the number of columns

    • Most important as analysis methods often prefer this form

  • pivot_wider()

    • widens data by increasing the number of columns and decreasing the number of rows

This is achieved via chaining/piping by using the pivot_longer() function via the tidyr package`. We also rename the data to sheet1a_long.

#make data long from wide format
sheet1a_long <- mysheet1a %>%
  pivot_longer(col=ends_with("D"), names_to = "enroll", values_to="value")
  1. One of the new columns should now correspond to the old column names that end with a “D”. (All columns in these census data files will have this similar format. The first three characters represent the survey with the next four representing the type of value you have from that survey. The last two digits prior to the “D” represent the year of the measurement. For more about the variables see the data information sheet).
  • Parse the string to pull out the year and convert the year into a numeric value such as 1997 or 2002.

Here, we use the mutate() function from the dplyr package to create this new year variable. There are intermediate steps / variables that also need to be considered in the way I carried out my logic to get the correct result for year.

I first take my long data and substring the enroll variable to capture the last two digits of the year via the substr() function. Since this variable has the same structure throughout, I can easily grab these two digits for every record – they are in position 8 and 9 of the string and I named the variable year_sub2. In order to create the year variable in the format requested (with prefix 19 or 20 as required), I needed to use an ifelse() conditional statement. I conditioned on the fact that if the last two digits of the year were between 00 and 22 (the current year), then I concatenate a “20” in front of the existing two digits via the paste() function if the condition was TRUE (first argument after conditional). If the condition was FALSE (second argument after conditional), I concatenate a “19” in front of the existing two digits form the year_sub2 variable and named this variable year_4c. Finally, I converted year4c to a numeric variable via the as.numeric() function and named it year.

#create 4 digit year numeric date
year_a <- sheet1a_long %>%
  mutate (year_sub2 = substr(x=enroll, start=8, stop=9), year4c = ifelse( 00 <= year_sub2 & year_sub2 <= 22 , paste0("20",year_sub2), paste0("19",year_sub2) ), year= as.numeric(year4c) )
  • Grab the first three characters and following four digits to create a new variable representing which measurement was grabbed.
    • Hint: Check out the substr() function from base R.

Here I use substr() again to grab the first three characters and four digits to create new variable for measurement ID and I named it measure – positions 1 thorough 7 in the string.

#grab first 3 characters and 4 digits to create new variable for measurement ID
measure_a <- year_a %>%
  mutate (measure = substr(x=enroll, start=1, stop=7) )
  1. Create two data sets

  • one data set that contains only non-county data

  • one data set that contains only county level data

Note that all county measurements have the format “County Name, DD” where “DD” represents the state. This can be used to subset the data. I used the code grep(pattern = ", \\w\\w", Area_name) to get the indices corresponding to states.

In this fourth step, we are creating two data sets from our measure_a data – one containing only non-county data and the other that contains only the county level data. I do this by utilizing the filter() function along with the code provided in the Note above; although, I opted to use grepl() instead because grep() returns a vector of indices of the element if a pattern exists in that vector while grepl() returns TRUE if the given pattern is present in the vector. Otherwise, it returns FALSE. It is like a bouillon with a conditional, making it easier for me to subset / filter my data. Here I create the data set noncounty_a when the pattern does not exist and data set county_a when the pattern does exist from the data set meansure_a.

#creating non-county data set
noncounty_a <- measure_a %>%
  filter(grepl(pattern = ", \\w\\w", area_name) == FALSE)  

#creating county data set
county_a <- measure_a %>%
  filter(grepl(pattern = ", \\w\\w", area_name))

For the county level data, add a class to the tibble called county. Similarly, add a class to the non-county data called state. This can be done by overwriting the class() you see on the object:

class(your_county_tibble) <- c("county", class(your_county_tibble))

We were also instructed to add a class to our tibbles – county for county level data and state for the non-county data via the class() function.

#adding a class to county level data
class(county_a) <- c("county", class(county_a))
#class(county_a)

#adding a class to non-county level data
class(noncounty_a) <- c("state", class(noncounty_a))
#class(noncounty_a)
  1. For the county level tibble, create a new variable that describes which state one of these county measurements corresponds to (the two digit abbreviation is fine, see substr()).

In step five, we create a new variable for the county level data, that I called state, where we have the abbreviation of the state for each county that a measurement corresponds to. I used mustate()to create the new variable and str_sub() to do my substringing from the stringr package. I subset the string for the variable area_name starting at the -2 indexing position, which basically counts backwards from the last character (default for last character is end = -1L).

# creating new variable that describes state of each county - 2 digit abbreviation
county_state_a <- county_a %>%
  mutate(state = stringr::str_sub(string=area_name, start = -2, end = -1L))
  1. For the non-county level tibble, create a new variable called “division” corresponding to the state’s classification of division here. If row corresponds to a non-state (i.e. UNITED STATES), return ERROR for the division. The code for this part will not be a ton of fun but can be made easier with the use of %in%.

For this last part, we had to reference a Wikipedia page that listed out all of the divisions each state was in, in order to create a new variable that I called division from the noncounty_a data. I did this by applying nested ifelse() functions that included %in to account for all the states I was interested for a particular division. We created the new variable via the mutate() function and to hold all the elements of interest (the states) we use the c() function to combines the arguments included. If the state included in the ifelse() function was met, then we return a certain division. If the condition was not met them we moved on to the next ifelse() condition. In the end, we had 9 divisions that all the states could fall into. I also used the tolower() function to account for any casing issues (e.g. DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA vs. District of Columbia). If there was a non-state in the area_name variable, we returned ERROR. I made comments at the end of each ifelse() closing parentheses to keep track of where I was. I found that this was very helpful, along with proper spacing and indentation, to successfully write out the syntax with minimal revisions due to syntax mistakes.

my_wrapper <- function(url=NULL, default_var_name = "enroll") {
#a <- read_csv_code(...)
#b <- function_for_step_1_2(a, ...)

#return final result
d
} #end of my_wrapper function

In the step below, we are trying to combine our two data sets/tibbles we got as a result of our my_wrapper() function calls by creating a small function. We are making sure that the two county level data sets, a and b, get combined and that our two non-county level data sets, a and b, get combined. This is achieved with the dplyr::bind_rows() function per the professors instructions.

My small function is called small_combo_func() and it has two parameters; one for the first object and one for the second object. In this case, we are inputting our lists (county_noncounty_list_a and county_noncounty_list_b) that we created and indexing each carefully to make sure the correct data has been combined. We store these two combined data sets in a list via list() and I store this output into an object called combine.

small_combo_func <- function(dat_a=NULL, dat_b=NULL) {

combine_county <- dplyr::bind_rows(dat_a[[1]], dat_b[[1]])
combine_noncounty <- dplyr::bind_rows(dat_a[[2]], dat_b[[2]])
  
list(combine_county, combine_noncounty)

} #end of small_combo_func function

#combine_noncounty <- small_combo_func(dat_a=noncounty_a, dat_b=noncounty_b)

combine <- small_combo_func(dat_a=county_noncounty_list_a, dat_b=county_noncounty_list_b)

First steps

We take a moment here to look at these different programming methods to look into the idea of object oriented programming and method dispatch. These lines of code below both look at the class of iris and exp inorder to determine which plot is appropriate.

plot 

## function (x, y, ...)

Please see my plotting function for state below.

I have named this function plot.state(). This function has two parameters - one for the input data.frame/tibble and the other for the variable we want to get the mean values for in order to plot. We use the group_by() function to make sure our y-axis will be correctly grouped for the means of the statistic, the summarize() and mean() functions to get our means from the value variable, filter() to exclude the observations of the variable division with “ERROR” in them, and ggplot() and geom_line() to plot our data.

#my class state / division plotting method function
plot.state <- function(df=NULL, var_name = "value"){
  #code to find the means for each division and year (think tidyverse)
  #Use get(var_name) to reference the var_name in your call to mean(): mean(get(var_name))
  #For this, think group_by along with summarize (we did mutate in class, summarize is very similar)
  #remove the "ERROR" setting
  
  df %>% 
    group_by(year, division) %>%
    #summarize reduces df to one vector or value
    summarize( mean = mean(get(var_name)), .groups="keep" ) %>%
    filter( division != "ERROR" ) %>%
    ggplot(aes(x = year, y = mean, color = division)) + geom_line()
}

Now, we are are going to create a plotting function for the class county, which will be similar to the plotting function above, but with more flexibility.

In this function, we are interested in doing the following:

  • specify the state of interest, giving a default value if not specified

  • determine whether the ‘top’ or ‘bottom’ most counties should be looked at with a default for ‘top’

  • instruct how many of the ‘top’ or ‘bottom’ will be investigated with a default value of 5

Within your plot function you should:

  • filter the data to only include data from the state specified

  • find the overall mean of the statistic (use get(var_name) here as well) for each Area_name and sort those values from largest to smallest if ‘top’ is specified or smallest to largest if ‘bottom’ is specified

  • obtain the top or bottom x number of Area_names from the previous step where x is given by the user or the default

  • filter the data for this state to only include the Area_name’s from the previous part (this is the data we’ll use to plot)

Please example code used to create a line plot:

ggplot(_filtered_df_, aes(x = _your_year_variable_, y = get(var_name), color = Area_name)) +
geom_line()

In this plot we are no longer interested in plotting the means, but rather the actual statistic’s value. We only get the mean and sort the data in order to grab the states we are interested in from the original data. We are testing out the function plot(combine[[1]]) by running it a few time with different input arguments to see if it works.

#testing out plot() function on data class county
plot(combine[[1]])

It works!

In my plot.county function, I have five different parameters and a most of them have default options, such as the variable of interest, the state, top vs. bottom records after sorting, and the number of observations we would like to see in our output / plot.

We first have a data frame of interest that we would like the function to be run on. In this case, it would be the combine[[1]] data, which includes our combines county class data. We then filter the data to a particular state we are interested and group it by the area_name variable via the group_by() function for our overall means. Then, we are going to calculate the mean via the summarize() and mean() functions. This is stored into an object called state_mean.

After we have our subset state_mean data how we’d like and have our means calculated, we then begin to sort the data in order to grab the observations we are interested in plotting. We do this with if() and else if() conditionals. We can see that if the parameter top=bottom is equal to top, then we sort the means in descending order, but if the parameter equalsbottom, then we sort by ascending order via the arrange() function. This is stored in an object called state_top_bottom. If top nor bottom are specified, then there will be a message stating “Note: Please use ‘top’ or ‘bottom’ as the condition in top_bottom parameter for this function!” with the stop().

Finally, before plotting we want to store the number of observations output in an object called state_x. the number of observations has a default value of 5 specified in the obs parameter, but we can specify however any we would like.

The tricky part that I had a hard time understanding was the next step, but I think I understand now. Essentially, after all these steps to get to out state_x data, we then grab those area_names from the state_x data as filtering criteria in our original data frame we specified in the first parameter of out plot.county() function. This object is called county_plotdat

Once we subset the correctly, we pass county_plotdat through the ggplot() and geom_line() funcions for our final output. If we specify 5 obs, then the plot will return 5 lines in our graph.

Please see results below.

#my class county / state plotting method function
plot.county <- function(df=NULL, var_name = "value", state_abrv="NC", top_bottom="top", obs=5){
  
  state_mean<-df %>% 
    filter( state == state_abrv ) %>%  #logical comparison uses a double equals sign
    group_by(area_name) %>%
    summarize( mean = mean(get(var_name)), .groups="keep" )
  
  if (top_bottom == "top") {state_top_bottom <- state_mean %>%
    arrange(desc(mean)) 
  } # end of "top" condition
  
  else if (top_bottom == "bottom") {state_top_bottom <- state_mean %>%
    arrange(mean)
  } #end of "bottom" condition
  else {
    stop("Note: Please use 'top' or 'bottom' as the condition in top_bottom parameter for this function!")
  } #end of anything not "top" nor "bottom" condition 
    
    state_x <- head(state_top_bottom, n = obs)
    
  #data we will use to  based off the states we get in the steps above
  county_plotdat <- df %>% 
    filter ( area_name %in% (state_x$area_name) )
    
  ggplot(data = county_plotdat, mapping = aes(x = year, y = get(var_name), color = area_name)) +
    geom_line()
}

#testing out function
plot.county (df=combine[[1]], var_name = "value", state_abrv="NC", top_bottom="top", obs=5) 

plot.county (df=combine[[1]], var_name = "value", state_abrv="AL", top_bottom="bottom", obs=10)
